7","1302–1349":"1302–1349","1304–Male":"1304–Overleden","1269–Male":"1269–Overleden","1349":"1349","1304":"1304","1302":"1302","1269":"1269","1301":"1301","1367":"1367","1289":"1289","1330":"1330","3 October 1330":"3 oktober 1330","October 1330":"oktober 1330","1280":"1280","Newburn, Fife, Scotland":"Newburn, Fife, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Perth, Perthshire, Scotland":"Perth, Perthshire, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Perth, , Perth, Scotland":"Perth, Perthshire, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Perth, Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Perth, Perthshire, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1289–3 October 1330":"1289–3 October 1330","1289–1330":"1289–1330","1280–1367":"1280–1367","1302–1349":"1302–1349","1304–Male":"1304–Deceased","1269–Male":"1269–Deceased","1349":"1349","1304":"1304","1302":"1302","1269":"1269","1301":"1301","1367":"1367","1289":"1289","1330":"1330","3 October 1330":"3 October 1330","October 1330":"October 1330","1280":"1280","Newburn, Fife, Scotland":"Newburn, Fife, Scotland, United Kingdom","Perth, Perthshire, Scotland":"Perth, Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Perth, , Perth, Scotland":"Perth, Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Perth, Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Perth, Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Forbes","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from Forbes in Tullynessle, Aberdeenshire, so named from Gaelic <i>forba</i> ‘field, district’ + the locative suffix <i>-ais</i>. The placename is pronounced in two syllables, with the stress on the second, and the surname until recently reflected this. Today, however, it is generally a monosyllable.","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Firbhisigh</b> ‘son of <i>Fearbhisigh</i>’, a personal name composed of elements meaning ‘man’ + ‘prosperity’.","History: A family of this name (see 2 above) in Connacht was famous for its traditional historians, compilers of the Book of Lecan."],"variants":[{"name":"Fawbush","meanings":["Altered form of Scottish   Forbes  , which ispronounced as two syllables in Aberdeenshire. Compare   Forbush  ."]},{"name":"Forbus","meanings":["Altered form of Scottish   Forbes  , reflecting thetraditional pronunciation as two syllables."]},{"name":"Forbush","meanings":["Scottish: altered form of   Forbes  , which was traditionally pronounced as two syllables. This surname is now rare in Britain.","Altered form of German <b>Vorbusch</b>, a topographic name for someone living on the edge of a wood, from <i>vor</i> ‘in front of’ + North German <i>Busch</i> ‘wood, bush’."]},{"name":"Fobbs","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Forbes  ."]},{"name":"Furbush","meanings":["Probably an altered form of Scottish   Forbes  , which is traditionally pronounced as two syllables. Compare   Furbish  ."]},{"name":"Forbis","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Forbes  , reflecting the traditional pronunciation as two syllables."]},{"name":"Fobes","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Forbes  ."]},{"name":"Forbess","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Forbes  , reflecting the traditional pronunciation as two syllables."]}]},{"name":"Eleanor","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ellenor","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Eleanor  , the result of blending with   Ellen ."]},{"name":"Elenor","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."]},{"name":"Elinor","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Eleanor ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Eleanor Forbes was born in 1289, in Newburn, Fife, Scotland, United Kingdom as the daughter of Viscount John Forbes. She married Thomas Dempster Laird of Murisk in 1301, in Perth, Perthshire, Scotland. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. She died on 3 October 1330, in Perth, Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom, at the age of 41, and was buried in Perth, Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1289–3 October 1330":"1289–3. oktoober 1330","1289–1330":"1289–1330","1280–1367":"1280–1367","1302–1349":"1302–1349","1304–Male":"1304–Surnud","1269–Male":"1269–Surnud","1349":"1349","1304":"1304","1302":"1302","1269":"1269","1301":"1301","1367":"1367","1289":"1289","1330":"1330","3 October 1330":"3. oktoober 1330","October 1330":"oktoober 1330","1280":"1280","Newburn, Fife, Scotland":"Newburn, Fife, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Perth, Perthshire, Scotland":"Perth, Perthshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Perth, , Perth, Scotland":"Perth, Perthshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Perth, Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Perth, Perthshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1289–3 October 1330":"1289–3. lokakuuta 1330","1289–1330":"1289–1330","1280–1367":"1280–1367","1302–1349":"1302–1349","1304–Male":"1304–Kuollut","1269–Male":"1269–Kuollut","1349":"1349","1304":"1304","1302":"1302","1269":"1269","1301":"1301","1367":"1367","1289